The Shift (clean and simple)

Old constraint:
	•	Code
	•	Skill
	•	Access

New constraint:
	•	Attention
	•	Distribution
	•	Trust
	•	Narrative

Everyone can now build the sword.
Very few can convince others it’s the one worth carrying.

⸻

What actually wins now (and will keep winning)

Think of this like layers of gravity pulling users in:

1. Distribution > Product
If nobody sees it, it doesn’t exist.
	•	Audience before product beats product before audience
	•	Built-in distribution loops (sharing, virality, referrals) matter more than features
	•	Channels > code

👉 A mediocre app with distribution beats a great app without it.

⸻

2. Narrative > Features
People don’t download features—they buy stories.
	•	“This app helps you track workouts” ❌
	•	“This is what Navy SEALs use to stay disciplined” ✅

Same tool. Different gravity.

Narrative is your entry point into attention space.

⸻

3. Trust > Novelty
Too many options = people default to safety signals:
	•	Brand
	•	Reviews
	•	Familiar faces
	•	Consistency

That’s why personal brands are exploding.

👉 In a saturated world, people choose people, not products.

⸻

4. Specificity > Generality
Broad apps drown. Sharp ones cut through.
	•	“AI productivity app” ❌
	•	“AI for loan officers to close deals faster” ✅

You don’t win by being bigger.
You win by being more precise.

⸻

5. Experience > Capability
Everyone has similar power now.

So what differentiates:
	•	Feel
	•	Flow
	•	Simplicity
	•	Delight

👉 The app that feels better wins, even if it does less.

⸻

The real meta shift

We’re entering:

The Age of Curation and Signal

Where the highest value person is not:
	•	the builder
	•	but the filter

The one who says:

“Out of 10,000 tools… use these 3.”

That’s authority.

That’s leverage.

⸻

So how do you win in this world?

Not by competing on raw building.

You stack advantages:

1. Build fast (commodity now)
2. Package it with identity
3. Attach it to a narrative
4. Distribute relentlessly
5. Narrow the target until it hurts

⸻

A simple winning formula

(Identity + Problem + Proof + Distribution)

Example:

“I help loan officers close 2x more deals using AI workflows I built myself.”

Now:
	•	Identity → loan officers
	•	Problem → closing deals
	•	Proof → 2x
	•	Distribution → content showing it working

That beats:

“Cool AI app I made.”

